It was originally an idea for a filler between the lower and the upper arm, we have two tattoos between those parts and we were discussing how we're gonna stuff our ideas in between those two.

We end up realized that the visuals didn't work in ways that we both envisioned, so after an hour of trying to fit everything in, I decided to pop the idea of switching it to somewhere else. And through some drawings and chat and throwing discussion, we have our results of "wtf is this❤️"
And it turns out pretty good!
This is my first time on doing a tattoo without a total sketch of reference especially for the colours. To be honest I was pretty nervous half way and kept asking myself how I'm gonna do this and make it look great. But after going through a roller coaster in my head, I'm happy that it turned out well and great. :) A lot of trust had gone into this process, and I'm blessed with a trusting client and calm minded me, so I get to work this out. :)
Can't wait for more challenges like this!!

Filler one: A worm eaten Apple with a cute touch into it.

The best part about Old school Tattoo style is that we can play around between a slightly more serious feature or something more fun and crazy. Client was leaning to a much classic approach for his whole plan about his leg, but I also think that is okay to have something fun and a little stupid sometimes to add a little touch of humour into the plan, and it turns out super fun and amazing 😻

Not a tattoo post-
Passing by a old shop that sells really interesting looking ceramics, a lady came out to greet me with a big smile on her face.
I was amazed by the colours and how nice looking the ceramics are, and the lady told me all these pieces are all made by the 80+ years old uncle that lived at the  back of the shop. 
After a short chat, the uncle came out and say hi to me with a warm smile. I was a little worried that I might look intimidating to him with my full tattoos, but despite all my worries, I'm able to use my broken Japanese and the help of Google translate, to express the appreciation of his work, and is inspiring he still continues to make all these till this day. :) I bought three items from the shop as a gift, once again I thanked him for his amazing art, and wished him the best of health, then I head off to my next destination. :)

My girl is baaaaaack 🖤
